00:26:41,500 --> 00:26:47,400
You know, if you ever do get a vibe from Bree that
she's interested in more than just friendship,

513
00:26:47,400 --> 00:26:50,300
I'd be careful if I were you.

514
00:26:50,300 --> 00:26:51,000
Excuse me?

515
00:26:51,000 --> 00:26:56,200
I just want you to know that she'd only be using
you to even the score with me.

516
00:26:56,200 --> 00:26:59,800
Don't fall for it.

517
00:26:59,800 --> 00:27:02,000
Bree would never do anything like that.
She's a lady.

518
00:27:02,000 --> 00:27:06,600
Exactly. A very beautiful, classy lady.

519
00:27:06,600 --> 00:27:12,600
Remember, they tend to end up
with doctors, not pharmacists.

520
00:27:12,600 --> 00:27:16,200
&nbsp;

521
00:27:16,200 --> 00:27:22,800
Bree is very beautiful and very classy,
but she's not very perceptive.

522
00:27:22,800 --> 00:27:28,000
For instance, she thinks you're a good person,
and it's now very clear to me

523
00:27:28,000 --> 00:27:31,700
you aren't.

524
00:27:31,700 --> 00:27:34,000
&nbsp;

525
00:27:34,000 --> 00:27:38,200
I'd like my prescription now, George.

526
00:27:38,200 --> 00:27:41,600
&nbsp;

527
00:27:41,600 --> 00:27:43,200
<font color=lightgreen>- R. VAN DE KAMP -

528
00:27:43,200 --> 00:27:46,100
&nbsp;

529
00:27:46,100 --> 00:27:48,200
I can't seem to find it.

530
00:27:48,200 --> 00:27:50,900
Guess I'll have to have it delivered.

531
00:27:50,900 --> 00:27:52,600
Thank you.

532
00:27:52,600 --> 00:27:55,400
No. Thank you.

533
00:27:55,400 --> 00:28:42,000
&nbsp;

534
00:28:42,000 --> 00:28:43,100
Paul.

535
00:28:43,100 --> 00:28:47,000
Did you notice? They're playing a classic.

536
00:28:47,000 --> 00:28:47,600
&nbsp;

537
00:28:47,600 --> 00:28:49,400
Yeah.

538
00:28:49,400 --> 00:28:51,400
Care to dance?

539
00:28:51,400 --> 00:28:55,400
&nbsp;

540
00:28:55,400 --> 00:28:56,400
I'd love to.

541
00:28:56,400 --> 00:29:07,300
&nbsp;

542
00:29:07,300 --> 00:29:09,700
I have a little confession to make.

543
00:29:09,700 --> 00:29:10,900
Oh?

544
00:29:10,900 --> 00:29:16,600
I have been so concerned about Julie lately that
I sort of eavesdropped on her the other day

545
00:29:16,600 --> 00:29:19,700
while she was having a phone conversation with Zach.

546
00:29:19,700 --> 00:29:22,000
Really.

547
00:29:22,000 --> 00:29:25,100
They were having a very interesting conversation.

548
00:29:25,100 --> 00:29:27,100
About?

549
00:29:27,100 --> 00:29:32,400
Zach was telling Julie about what happened to Dana.

550
00:29:32,400 --> 00:29:34,100
Was he now?

551
00:29:34,100 --> 00:29:37,300
Yes.

552
00:29:37,300 --> 00:29:37,600
&nbsp;

553
00:29:37,600 --> 00:29:39,600
How much did you hear?

554
00:29:39,600 --> 00:29:42,300
Everything.

555
00:29:42,300 --> 00:29:46,500
&nbsp;

556
00:29:46,500 --> 00:29:49,500
You realize it was an accident.

557
00:29:49,500 --> 00:29:53,000
Oh, of course. I assumed as much.

558
00:29:53,000 --> 00:29:56,400
He didn't mean to kill Dana.

559
00:29:56,400 --> 00:29:57,100
&nbsp;

560
00:29:57,100 --> 00:30:00,300
He was practically a baby himself.

561
00:30:00,300 --> 00:30:02,600
He didn't understand what he was doing.

562
00:30:02,600 --> 00:30:04,900
No, of course he didn't.

563
00:30:04,900 --> 00:30:09,200
So what happened exactly?

564
00:30:09,200 --> 00:30:12,600
Mary Alice and in ever really knew.

565
00:30:12,600 --> 00:30:15,000
We heard the baby screaming.

566
00:30:15,000 --> 00:30:17,400
By the time we got up to the crib, it was too late.

567
00:30:17,400 --> 00:30:21,100
Paul, I am so sorry.

568
00:30:21,100 --> 00:30:24,300
Thank you.

569
00:30:24,300 --> 00:30:28,800
&nbsp;

570
00:30:28,800 --> 00:30:33,200
So you and Mary Alice just kept this
to yourselves all these years?

571
00:30:33,200 --> 00:30:36,000
It was a very dark chapter in our lives.

572
00:30:36,000 --> 00:30:39,300
We preferred not to relive it.

573
00:30:39,300 --> 00:30:42,600
It was also a private family matter.

574
00:30:42,600 --> 00:30:46,400
I'd appreciate your discretion.

575
00:30:46,400 --> 00:30:52,800
&nbsp;

576
00:30:52,800 --> 00:30:55,200
Sure.

577
00:30:55,200 --> 00:31:13,000
&nbsp;

578
00:31:13,000 --> 00:31:15,100
Look...

579
00:31:15,100 --> 00:31:17,400
I want you to know that I'm really sorry I talked to Julie,

580
00:31:17,400 --> 00:31:20,400
but she did promise me that she wasn't
going to say anything to her mom.

581
00:31:20,400 --> 00:31:23,700
It's okay. I handled Susan.

582
00:31:23,700 --> 00:31:25,400
Good.

583
00:31:25,400 --> 00:31:29,500
But we need to talk about these things
that you think you remember.

584
00:31:29,500 --> 00:31:32,600
They're not true.

585
00:31:32,600 --> 00:31:35,200
How can they not be true?

586
00:31:35,200 --> 00:31:38,700
Memories lie, Zach.

587
00:31:38,700 --> 00:31:39,300
&nbsp;

588
00:31:39,300 --> 00:31:44,000
You didn't kill anyone.

589
00:31:44,000 --> 00:31:47,000
&nbsp;

590
00:31:47,000 --> 00:31:50,800
Dana is very much alive.

591
00:31:50,800 --> 00:32:05,600
&nbsp;

592
00:32:05,600 --> 00:32:07,600
Hi. What are you doing here?

593
00:32:07,600 --> 00:32:09,500
Where is it?

594
00:32:09,500 --> 00:32:11,900
- What?
- The ring, Gabrielle. My grandmother's ring.

595
00:32:11,900 --> 00:32:15,500
John caught me off-guard.
Obviously, I'm going to give back the ring.

596
00:32:15,500 --> 00:32:22,000
Well, you better, because make no mistake,
if you try to ruin my son's life,

597
00:32:22,000 --> 00:32:23,600
I will ruin yours.

598
00:32:23,600 --> 00:32:25,700
Helen, okay. Go to the car.

599
00:32:25,700 --> 00:32:30,100
Come on, please.
Just -- please.

600
00:32:30,100 --> 00:32:32,600
&nbsp;

601
00:32:32,600 --> 00:32:37,900
Obviously, I'm not leaving my husband
and marrying John.

602
00:32:37,900 --> 00:32:40,200
Well, I think that's wise.

603
00:32:40,200 --> 00:32:42,200
I-I'll talk to John tomorrow and give back the ring.

604
00:32:42,200 --> 00:32:47,500
Okay, good, good.
Um, we appreciate everything you've done.

605
00:32:47,500 --> 00:32:49,900
Hey, Bob.

606
00:32:49,900 --> 00:32:56,900
I get why she's so angry with me, but what
I don't get is why you're so nice.

607
00:32:56,900 --> 00:32:58,500
Well, John's a big boy.

608
00:32:58,500 --> 00:33:02,900
Whatever happened between the two of you
is his mistake as much as yours.

609
00:33:02,900 --> 00:33:05,100
I guess.

610
00:33:05,100 --> 00:33:10,800
I understand if, uh, if you hate me just a little.

611
00:33:10,800 --> 00:33:20,600
&nbsp;

612
00:33:20,600 --> 00:33:25,000
When I was a kid, I always played by the rules.

613
00:33:25,000 --> 00:33:30,800
I never cheated on a test, never even missed a curfew.

614
00:33:30,800 --> 00:33:34,700
But I can't help but think...

615
00:33:34,700 --> 00:33:40,100
how wonderful it would have been to have made
at least one mistake like you.

616
00:33:40,100 --> 00:33:41,700
&nbsp;

617
00:33:41,700 --> 00:33:45,700
That's sweet. You're -- you're very sweet.

618
00:33:45,700 --> 00:33:49,100
Yeah. I'm a little sweet.

619
00:33:49,100 --> 00:33:50,000
&nbsp;

620
00:33:50,000 --> 00:33:54,300
Mostly I'm just middle-aged.

621
00:33:54,300 --> 00:34:05,600
&nbsp;

622
00:34:05,600 --> 00:34:07,900
<font color=lightgreen>- SOLD -

623
00:34:07,900 --> 00:34:12,000
&nbsp;

624
00:34:12,000 --> 00:34:13,900
Are you okay?

625
00:34:13,900 --> 00:34:17,500
I know this is a lotto digest all at once.

626
00:34:17,500 --> 00:34:19,200
I'm fine.

627
00:34:19,200 --> 00:34:22,900
I'm just happy you finally told me the truth.

628
00:34:22,900 --> 00:34:23,900
&nbsp;

629
00:34:23,900 --> 00:34:29,400
One thing, though -- why are you telling me all this now?

630
00:34:29,400 --> 00:34:33,100
I couldn't let you keep thinking that you killed someone.

631
00:34:33,100 --> 00:34:35,300
No one should carry that kind of burden.

632
00:34:35,300 --> 00:34:37,500
Or you just didn't want me running my mouth.

633
00:34:37,500 --> 00:34:38,600
That's not what it's about.

634
00:34:38,600 --> 00:34:41,500
Yes, it is.

635
00:34:41,500 --> 00:34:43,600
&nbsp;

636
00:34:43,600 --> 00:34:45,900
I won't tell anyone.

637
00:34:45,900 --> 00:34:48,600
I'll keep your secret.

638
00:34:48,600 --> 00:34:49,600
&nbsp;

639
00:34:49,600 --> 00:34:52,500
Dad.

640
00:34:52,500 --> 00:34:54,200
Thank you.

641
00:34:54,200 --> 00:34:57,600
But we're not moving.

642
00:34:57,600 --> 00:35:01,000
That's out of the question.

643
00:35:01,000 --> 00:35:01,600
&nbsp;

644
00:35:01,600 --> 00:35:06,400
Well, I'm not leaving Julie, and if you
want my support, that's the deal.

645
00:35:06,400 --> 00:35:08,300
And if I refuse?

646
00:35:08,300 --> 00:35:11,000
You won't.

647
00:35:11,000 --> 00:35:23,600
&nbsp;

648
00:35:23,600 --> 00:35:25,400
So here's the thing --

649
00:35:25,400 --> 00:35:29,000
I feel really awful about how I acted before.

650
00:35:29,000 --> 00:35:31,600
For god's sake, Lynette, you threw
me out of my own house.

651
00:35:31,600 --> 00:35:36,600
I overreacted, I know. I'm sorry.

652
00:35:36,600 --> 00:35:38,100
Look...

653
00:35:38,100 --> 00:35:45,100
I know you love my mom, but how she decides to live
her life, it's just --it's entirely up to her.

654
00:35:45,100 --> 00:35:47,900
You're right. You're right.

655
00:35:47,900 --> 00:35:48,300
&nbsp;

656
00:35:48,300 --> 00:35:54,000
I guess I just got so upset because... oh, whatever.

657
00:35:54,000 --> 00:35:58,100
Let's not beat a dead horse. It's over.
I'm sorry. Good night.

658
00:35:58,100 --> 00:36:04,400
&nbsp;

659
00:36:04,400 --> 00:36:06,200
Okay, get it off your chest.

660
00:36:06,200 --> 00:36:09,500
Well, you knew your dad was having an affair,
and it didn't seem to bother you that much,

661
00:36:09,500 --> 00:36:14,500
and that worries me, because if you can find it
in you to condone something like that,

662
00:36:14,500 --> 00:36:19,100
then what's going to happen when you've
been on the road for 40 years?

663
00:36:19,100 --> 00:36:20,600
Lynette...

664
00:36:20,600 --> 00:36:23,300
I'm not my father.

665
00:36:23,300 --> 00:36:25,000
I know. Of course.

666
00:36:25,000 --> 00:36:28,800
You're not your father.

667
00:36:28,800 --> 00:36:32,800
&nbsp;

668
00:36:32,800 --> 00:36:37,400
And just so we're absolutely clear,
I am definitely not your mother,

669
00:36:37,400 --> 00:36:40,000
because if you ever betray me, I will leave you.

670
00:36:40,000 --> 00:36:46,100
I will take the kids, and I will walk out that door,
and you will never see any of us again.

671
00:36:46,100 --> 00:36:46,300
&nbsp;

672
00:36:46,300 --> 00:36:51,400
Whoo. Glad to get that off my chest.
Thank you. I love you.

673
00:36:51,400 --> 00:37:00,500
&nbsp;

674
00:37:00,500 --> 00:37:01,600
Couldn't sleep, huh?

675
00:37:01,600 --> 00:37:02,700
No.

676
00:37:02,700 --> 00:37:05,600
Me either.

677
00:37:05,600 --> 00:37:05,900
&nbsp;

678
00:37:05,900 --> 00:37:08,200
I'm so sorry about the ruckus I caused.

679
00:37:08,200 --> 00:37:10,900
It's okay. I'm not, uh...

680
00:37:10,900 --> 00:37:12,800
I'm not upset about that.

681
00:37:12,800 --> 00:37:13,500
No?

682
00:37:13,500 --> 00:37:15,800
No.

683
00:37:15,800 --> 00:37:16,500
&nbsp;

684
00:37:16,500 --> 00:37:19,500
What's wrong?

685
00:37:19,500 --> 00:37:20,200
&nbsp;

686
00:37:20,200 --> 00:37:24,900
There's something that Lynette doesn't know about,
dad -- something that I did.

687
00:37:24,900 --> 00:37:29,100
And I don't know what's going to happen
if she ever finds out.

688
00:37:29,100 --> 00:37:30,300
&nbsp;

689
00:37:30,300 --> 00:37:36,000
<font color=yellow>The next morning, Gabrielle returned the
engagement ring to her former lover,

690
00:37:36,000 --> 00:37:40,100
<font color=yellow>a gesture that was met with... measured enthusiasm.

691
00:37:40,100 --> 00:37:41,500
Please, calm down.

692
00:37:41,500 --> 00:37:44,900
This doesn't make any sense, okay?
You love me. I know you love me.

693
00:37:44,900 --> 00:37:46,300
Love isn't enough.

694
00:37:46,300 --> 00:37:49,300
Where would we live --here, with your roommates?

695
00:37:49,300 --> 00:37:51,100
The only decoration in the bathroom is a bong.

696
00:37:51,100 --> 00:37:52,500
We could get our own place.

697
00:37:52,500 --> 00:37:54,500
How? You're barely making minimum wage.

698
00:37:54,500 --> 00:37:57,400
Okay, sure, we'd be poor at first, but we'd be happy.

699
00:37:57,400 --> 00:38:01,200
I've tried poor but happy.
Guess what --it wasn't that happy.

700
00:38:01,200 --> 00:38:05,500
Mr. Solis is going to jail.
You want to stick around for that?

701
00:38:05,500 --> 00:38:06,900
I don't know.

702
00:38:06,900 --> 00:38:11,500
You know, every once in a while,
even I want to do the right thing.

703
00:38:11,500 --> 00:38:16,000
Mrs. Solis, I love you so much.

704
00:38:16,000 --> 00:38:20,400
I mean, doesn't that mean anything to you?

705
00:38:20,400 --> 00:38:21,700
&nbsp;

706
00:38:21,700 --> 00:38:24,400
Honestly, no.

707
00:38:24,400 --> 00:38:27,800
John, you're a toy -- a sweet, dumb toy,

708
00:38:27,800 --> 00:38:34,400
so you might as well go to college,
because you and me -- no future.

709
00:38:34,400 --> 00:38:41,400
&nbsp;

710
00:38:41,400 --> 00:38:44,100
Ms. Mayer, hey. Is Julie home?

711
00:38:44,100 --> 00:38:45,800
She's in the shower.

712
00:38:45,800 --> 00:38:47,100
Oh.

713
00:38:47,100 --> 00:38:50,100
Well, I just came by to give her some good news.

714
00:38:50,100 --> 00:38:52,200
What's that?

715
00:38:52,200 --> 00:38:55,800
Well, it turns out that my dad
and I aren't moving after all.

716
00:38:55,800 --> 00:38:56,700
What?

717
00:38:56,700 --> 00:39:00,900
Yeah, he reconsidered, so I guess
we're going to keep living across the street.

718
00:39:00,900 --> 00:39:02,700
Okay.

719
00:39:02,700 --> 00:39:07,000
Wow, uh... wow.

720
00:39:07,000 --> 00:39:11,600
You know, uh, c-can you sit down?
I-I need to talk to you.

721
00:39:11,600 --> 00:39:15,200
&nbsp;

722
00:39:15,200 --> 00:39:18,500
Hey.

723
00:39:18,500 --> 00:39:21,900
&nbsp;

724
00:39:21,900 --> 00:39:25,300
Do you know that Julie is the first girl
I ever gave a flower to?

725
00:39:25,300 --> 00:39:26,100
Really?

726
00:39:26,100 --> 00:39:28,500
Yeah.

727
00:39:28,500 --> 00:39:31,600
Yeah, I-I really like her, Ms. Mayer.

728
00:39:31,600 --> 00:39:34,600
Zach, um...

729
00:39:34,600 --> 00:39:34,900
&nbsp;

730
00:39:34,900 --> 00:39:37,200
Julie is only 14 years old,

731
00:39:37,200 --> 00:39:43,100
and sometimes girls, when they're that age,
they just don't always make the right decisions,

732
00:39:43,100 --> 00:39:50,400
and, um... as her mother, it is
my responsibility to protect her.

733
00:39:50,400 --> 00:39:53,100
You want to protect her from me?

734
00:39:53,100 --> 00:39:57,100
No, I-I just --

735
00:39:57,100 --> 00:40:00,000
I think that you should slow things down.

736
00:40:00,000 --> 00:40:05,300
I-I want you to not see her for a while.

737
00:40:05,300 --> 00:40:07,300
No.

738
00:40:07,300 --> 00:40:08,300
"No"?

739
00:40:08,300 --> 00:40:11,200
You're not taking her away from me.

740
00:40:11,200 --> 00:40:11,400
&nbsp;

741
00:40:11,400 --> 00:40:15,900
Listen, I know being dramatic is the birth
right of every teenager, but come on.

742
00:40:15,900 --> 00:40:17,900
Why are you laughing?!

743
00:40:17,900 --> 00:40:21,000
Do you think this is funny?

744
00:40:21,000 --> 00:40:21,600
&nbsp;

745
00:40:21,600 --> 00:40:24,800
Thank you, Zach.
You have just made this really easy for me.

746
00:40:24,800 --> 00:40:28,200
You are now forbidden from seeing or
talking to my daughter ever again,

747
00:40:28,200 --> 00:40:33,800
and if you come within 10 feet of her, I will call the police,
and I will have you arrested. Now get out.

748
00:40:33,800 --> 00:41:00,200
&nbsp;

749
00:41:00,200 --> 00:41:07,900
<font color=yellow>Sooner or later, the time comes when we
all must become responsible adults

750
00:41:07,900 --> 00:41:08,900
&nbsp;

751
00:41:08,900 --> 00:41:16,100
<font color=yellow>and learn to give up what we want so
we can choose to do what is right.

752
00:41:16,100 --> 00:41:19,700
&nbsp;

753
00:41:19,700 --> 00:41:26,100
<font color=yellow>Of course, a life time of responsibility isn't always easy.

754
00:41:26,100 --> 00:41:30,300
&nbsp;

755
00:41:30,300 --> 00:41:38,100
<font color=yellow>And as the years go on, it's a burden
that can become too heavy for some to bear.

756
00:41:38,100 --> 00:41:45,100
<font color=yellow>But still, we try to do what is best, what is good --
not only for ourselves...

757
00:41:45,100 --> 00:41:50,100
<font color=yellow>but for those we love.

758
00:41:50,100 --> 00:41:55,000
&nbsp;

759
00:41:55,000 --> 00:41:56,300
Hey.

760
00:41:56,300 --> 00:41:57,700
I'm glad you came.

761
00:41:57,700 --> 00:42:02,300
Zach, I can't stay long.
If my mom catches me, she'll freak.

762
00:42:02,300 --> 00:42:04,500
Come here.

763
00:42:04,500 --> 00:42:08,400
&nbsp;

764
00:42:08,400 --> 00:42:10,900
She said I can't see you anymore.

765
00:42:10,900 --> 00:42:13,600
What are we going to do?

766
00:42:13,600 --> 00:42:17,100
I'm not sure.

767
00:42:17,100 --> 00:42:19,600
&nbsp;

768
00:42:19,600 --> 00:42:25,800
<font color=yellow>Yes, sooner or later,
we must all become responsible adults.

769
00:42:25,800 --> 00:42:31,300
<font color=yellow>No one knows this better than the young.

770
00:42:31,300 --> 00:42:41,300
&nbsp;